The big bang vs drip drip approach to D+I is a good topic.

=20

I like the narrative around drip drip =E2=80=93 establish what your =
culture is today and then nudge it progressively towards a D+I focus by =
changing cultural dimensions, actions statements and consistent =
messaging =E2=80=93 both targeted and broadcast.

=20

It won=E2=80=99t happen overnight =E2=80=93 it will take a year =
=E2=80=93 but in the context of our inability to address D+I issues over =
the past 100 years =E2=80=93 that is actually a short timeframe to apply =
real change.

=20

We can come up with an overall =E2=80=9Cbias score=E2=80=9D for the =
company that looks at the level of bias shown and how it has changed =
over time =E2=80=93 but as below what you are really measuring is mostly =
tribalism.

=20

However if we are going to apply a big bang approach I like some =
variation of:

=20

*	Making scores public to break down biases around promoting those that =
fit the accepted white male vision of power
*	Calculating team level bias scores and publishing them. These scores =
would depend on the instance but would probably be focussed on team =
tribalism (the easiest to measure) and gender (2nd easiest =E2=80=93 but =
can be confused with tribalism)
*	Devise training schemes to address common biases (women against women, =
men against women) and seed these programs using our metrics. My point =
is that until someone has come up with a training program that can =
address an individuals deep seated behavioural norms that have been =
driven by a lifetime of living in a patriarchal culture then there =
isn=E2=80=99t much point identifying those will more patriarchal views

=20

My problem is that I don=E2=80=99t think the big bang is palatable =
=E2=80=93 people may like to talk about it but they would never do it

=20

